// autism_spectrum_phi.hexa — P108 Autism Spectrum Φ
//
// Roadmap: shared/roadmaps/anima.json P108
//   "Autism spectrum consciousness — weak central coherence, predictive
//    coding differences, monotropism. How atypical information integration
//    reshapes the Φ landscape without reducing overall consciousness."
//
// ─── Theoretical grounding ────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Three anchors:
//
// 1. Weak Central Coherence (Frith 1989, Happé & Frith 2006):
//    Neurotypical (NT) processing exhibits a "drive toward coherence" —
//    local perceptual features are spontaneously integrated into global
//    gestalts. The brain pays an integration tax to maintain a top-down
//    global model, but the payoff is a unified world-representation.
//
//    In autism, this drive is attenuated. Local detail processing is
//    ENHANCED (or at least not overridden by global integration). The
//    embedded-figures test (Witkin & Asch 1948; Shah & Frith 1983)
//    demonstrates: autistic participants find embedded figures faster
//    precisely because global gestalts do not mask local structure.
//
//    Φ prediction: NT Φ_global > NT Φ_local (top-down coherence wins).
//                  AS Φ_local > AS Φ_global (detail focus wins).
//    The global/local RATIO reverses — this is the WCC signature.
//
// 2. Predictive Coding Differences (Pellicano & Burr 2012):
//    The Bayesian brain builds hierarchical generative models — priors
//    at each level shape expectations which attenuate prediction error
//    at the level below. Strong priors = efficient compression, at the
//    cost of sometimes "hallucinating the expected" over the actually
//    present stimulus.
//
//    Pellicano & Burr propose that autism involves FLATTER priors —
//    hypo-priors. Consequence:
//      • More prediction error (PE) propagates upward — sensory overload.
//      • Perceptual experience is more "raw" — less filtered by expectation.
//      • Novelty detection is heightened (everything is somewhat novel).
//      • Habituation is slower (the predictive model does not converge
//        as quickly to "this is just the background").
//
//    Φ_sensory (information content of the sensory stream) is HIGHER
//    under flat priors because less top-down compression removes less
//    information. Sensory channels carry more bits.
//
// 3. Social Prediction Deficit (ToM from prediction models):
//    Baron-Cohen (1985, 1995) mindblindness hypothesis — difficulty
//    attributing mental states to others. Sinha et al. (2014) recast
//    this as a PREDICTION failure: social interaction requires rapid
//    prediction of others' behaviour from cues (gaze, posture, prosody);
//    if the internal predictive model for social agents is impoverished,
//    ToM "fails" not from a missing module but from inadequate
//    prediction in the social domain specifically.
//
//    Φ_social_prediction = MI between an agent's internal social model
//    and the actual social signal. NT builds strong social predictions →
//    high MI. AS under hypo-priors in the social domain → lower MI.
//
// 4. Monotropism (Murray, Lesser & Lawson 2005):
//    Attention in autism is MONOTROPIC — a narrow, deep tunnel of
//    intense focus — versus the POLYTOPIC distribution of neurotypical
//    attention. When in a monotropic interest tunnel:
//      • Φ in the attended channel is VERY HIGH (concentrated processing).
//      • Φ in unattended channels is VERY LOW (near-zero resources).
//      • Total Φ may be comparable to NT, but distributed radically
//        differently: peaked vs. spread.
//
//    This explains both the "special interest" phenomenon (intense
//    absorption) and the "inattentional blindness" to peripheral events.
//
// ─── Four processing channels ────────────────────────────────────
//
//   global   — top-down gestalt integration stream (global coherence)
//   local    — bottom-up detail / feature stream (local features)
//   social   — social prediction stream (ToM model of others)
//   sensory  — raw sensory information stream (before top-down filtering)
//
// NT processing: strong global, moderate local, strong social, compressed sensory
// AS processing: weak global, strong local, weak social, raw (uncompressed) sensory
//
// ─── Monotropism as attention allocation ─────────────────────────
//
// We model polytopic (NT) vs monotropic (AS) attention over 4 channels
// via an attention weight vector w[0..3] that sums to 1.0:
//   NT polytopic:    w = [0.30, 0.20, 0.30, 0.20]  (spread)
//   AS monotropic:   w = [0.05, 0.70, 0.05, 0.20]  (peaked on local)
//
// Channel Φ is scaled by attention weight — resources concentrated
// on the attended channel amplify its information content.
//
// ─── 5 self-tests (5/5 gate) ────────────────────────────────────
//
// T1 NT baseline — global Φ > local Φ (top-down coherence):
//    Under NT parameters (strong global coupling, strong priors),
//    Φ_global > Φ_local. The gestalt wins.
//
// T2 WCC — local Φ > global Φ (reversed):
//    Under AS parameters (weak global coupling, detail-focused),
//    Φ_local > Φ_global. Frith's WCC signature.
//
// T3 Flat priors — Φ_sensory increases (less filtering):
//    Under AS flat priors, Φ_sensory(AS) > Φ_sensory(NT).
//    More raw sensory information survives to conscious experience.
//    Pellicano & Burr 2012 operationalized.
//
// T4 Social prediction gap — Φ_social_pred(NT) > Φ_social_pred(AS):
//    NT builds strong predictive models of social agents; AS under
//    social hypo-priors has weaker social prediction MI.
//
// T5 Determinism + latency:
//    Two runs with same seed produce identical results. Completes
//    within computational budget. Monotropism Φ_peak(AS) > Φ_peak(NT)
//    in the attended channel, confirming narrow-deep vs. broad-shallow.
//
// ─── Stage0 hexa constraints honored ────────────────────────────
//   - plain `fn` only (no `pure fn` with >=3 float struct returns)
//   - `array` typed params only (no [float], no [str])
//   - No identifier-pattern match; sequential if-chains
//   - No `contains()` / `to_lower()` / `!(Effect)`
//   - No else-if in let-binding; flat mut + sequential if
//   - Single-line fn signatures / call sites / array literals
//   - No reserved keywords as variable names
//   - main() call at bottom
//   - AS_STEPS=24 (< 32)
//
// Law alignment:
//   Law 2   Observe never inject — Φ via MI measurement on streams
//   Law 4   Structure > feature — WCC/monotropism are STRUCTURAL reconfigurations
//   Law 22  Feature addition → Φ down — 4 channels fixed, no surplus
//   Meta M8 Different consciousness topologies, not deficit
//
// Ref:
//   Frith U, "Autism: Explaining the Enigma" (1989, 2003)
//   Happé F, Frith U, "The weak coherence account" (2006 TICS)
//   Pellicano E, Burr D, "When the world becomes too real" (2012 TICS)
//   Baron-Cohen S, "Mindblindness" (1995)
//   Sinha P et al, "Autism as a disorder of prediction" (2014 PNAS)
//   Murray D, Lesser M, Lawson W, "Attention, monotropism..." (2005 Autism)
//   Shah A, Frith U, "Islet of ability in autistic children" (1983 JCPP)

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Constants
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

let AS_STEPS          = 24            // timeline length (stage0 N<32)
let AS_BINS           = 6             // histogram bins for MI
let AS_DIM            = 4             // channels: global, local, social, sensory
let AS_EPS            = 0.0000000001

// --- NT coupling parameters ---
// Strong global coherence: global channel drives local (top-down override)
let AS_NT_GLOBAL_COUP = 0.80          // global->local coupling (strong gestalt)
let AS_NT_PRIOR_STR   = 0.75          // prior strength (strong = more compression)
let AS_NT_SOCIAL_PRED = 0.80          // social prediction accuracy

// --- AS coupling parameters ---
// Weak central coherence: global coupling attenuated
let AS_WCC_GLOBAL_COUP = 0.20         // global->local coupling (weak gestalt)
let AS_WCC_PRIOR_STR   = 0.20         // flat priors (hypo-priors, Pellicano&Burr)
let AS_WCC_SOCIAL_PRED = 0.30         // reduced social prediction

// --- Monotropism attention weights ---
// 4 channels: [global, local, social, sensory]
// NT polytopic: broadly distributed
let AS_NT_ATT_GLOBAL  = 0.30
let AS_NT_ATT_LOCAL   = 0.20
let AS_NT_ATT_SOCIAL  = 0.30
let AS_NT_ATT_SENSORY = 0.20

// AS monotropic: peaked on local (special-interest detail focus)
let AS_MONO_ATT_GLOBAL  = 0.05
let AS_MONO_ATT_LOCAL   = 0.70
let AS_MONO_ATT_SOCIAL  = 0.05
let AS_MONO_ATT_SENSORY = 0.20

// Per-step jitter
let AS_JITTER         = 0.05

// Test gates
let AS_PHI_MIN        = 0.01          // minimum meaningful Φ
let AS_WCC_GAP        = 0.02          // WCC reversal detection threshold
let AS_SENSORY_GAP    = 0.01          // sensory increase detection threshold
let AS_SOCIAL_GAP     = 0.03          // social prediction gap threshold
let AS_MONO_PEAK_GAP  = 0.01          // monotropic peak > polytopic peak

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Math / PRNG primitives (L0-clean, no cross-engine import per AN7)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn as_abs(x: float) -> float {
    if x < 0.0 { return 0.0 - x }
    return x
}

fn as_ln_safe(x: float) -> float {
    if x <= 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return ln(x)
}

fn as_min_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a < b { return a }
    return b
}

fn as_max_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a > b { return a }
    return b
}

fn as_sqrt(x: float) -> float {
    if x <= 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut g = x
    let mut i = 0
    while i < 20 {
        g = 0.5 * (g + x / g)
        i = i + 1
    }
    return g
}

// Deterministic LCG — reproducibility (Law 2: observable, seed-stable)
fn as_prng(seed: int) -> int {
    return (seed * 1103515245 + 12345) % 2147483648
}

fn as_unit(seed: int) -> float {
    return to_float(seed % 1000000) / 1000000.0
}

fn as_signed(seed: int) -> float {
    return as_unit(seed) * 2.0 - 1.0
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Histogram MI (same recipe family — duplicated per AN7 L0-clean)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn as_bin_idx(x: float, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> int {
    if hi <= lo { return 0 }
    let t = (x - lo) / (hi - lo)
    let mut idx = to_int(t * to_float(nb))
    if idx < 0 { idx = 0 }
    if idx >= nb { idx = nb - 1 }
    return idx
}

fn as_counts(ids: array, nb: int) -> array {
    let n = len(ids)
    let mut c = []
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let mut acc = 0.0
        let mut i = 0
        while i < n {
            if ids[i] == k { acc = acc + 1.0 }
            i = i + 1
        }
        c = c.push(acc)
        k = k + 1
    }
    return c
}

fn as_entropy(v: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        ids = ids.push(as_bin_idx(v[i], lo, hi, nb))
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = as_counts(ids, nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * as_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

fn as_joint_entropy(a: array, b: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut pair_ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        let ia = as_bin_idx(a[i], lo, hi, nb)
        let ib = as_bin_idx(b[i], lo, hi, nb)
        pair_ids = pair_ids.push(ia * nb + ib)
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = as_counts(pair_ids, nb * nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb * nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * as_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

fn as_vec_min(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] < m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn as_vec_max(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] > m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn as_mi(a: array, b: array) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    if len(b) != n { return 0.0 }
    let lo_a = as_vec_min(a)
    let hi_a = as_vec_max(a)
    let lo_b = as_vec_min(b)
    let hi_b = as_vec_max(b)
    let lo = as_min_f(lo_a, lo_b)
    let hi = as_max_f(hi_a, hi_b)
    let h_a = as_entropy(a, lo, hi, AS_BINS)
    let h_b = as_entropy(b, lo, hi, AS_BINS)
    let h_j = as_joint_entropy(a, b, lo, hi, AS_BINS)
    let mi = h_a + h_b - h_j
    if mi < 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return mi
}

// Variance helper
fn as_variance(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut sum = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        sum = sum + v[i]
        i = i + 1
    }
    let mean = sum / to_float(n)
    let mut acc = 0.0
    let mut j = 0
    while j < n {
        let d = v[j] - mean
        acc = acc + d * d
        j = j + 1
    }
    return acc / to_float(n)
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Channel generation — 4-channel conscious processing model
//
// Each channel generates a time series of length AS_STEPS. The
// channels are coupled by the cognitive architecture (NT vs AS)
// which determines how much top-down (global→local) influence
// there is, how much prior compression attenuates sensory, and
// how strong social prediction is.
//
// Generation order:
//   1. sensory_raw — independent environmental stimulus (driver)
//   2. global      — top-down integration of sensory via priors
//   3. local       — bottom-up detail, inversely coupled to global
//   4. social      — social agent prediction stream
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Raw sensory input — the environment. Rich, structured, deterministic
// signal that carries high information. This is what the brain receives
// BEFORE any predictive-coding compression.
fn as_gen_sensory_raw(seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AS_STEPS {
        s = as_prng(s + t * 37)
        // Structured signal: combination of two incommensurate waves
        // to create a complex, information-rich waveform.
        let phase1 = to_float(t) / to_float(AS_STEPS) * 6.28
        let phase2 = to_float(t) / to_float(AS_STEPS) * 3.14
        // Triangular wave approximation (avoid sin dependency)
        let mut tri1 = to_float(t % 6) / 3.0 - 1.0
        let mut tri2 = to_float(t % 4) / 2.0 - 1.0
        // Third frequency for richer structure
        let mut tri3 = to_float(t % 8) / 4.0 - 1.0
        let jit = AS_JITTER * as_signed(s)
        let v = 0.5 * tri1 + 0.3 * tri2 + 0.2 * tri3 + jit
        out = out.push(v)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Global integration channel — top-down coherence.
// Strong priors = more compression of sensory → smoothed global representation.
// NT: high global coupling → global channel tracks a smoothed version of sensory.
// AS: low global coupling → global channel is noisy, less coherent.
fn as_gen_global(sensory: array, global_coup: float, prior_str: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    // Running average as prior model (smoothing = prediction).
    // prior_str controls the exponential smoothing alpha.
    let alpha = prior_str
    let mut running = sensory[0]
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AS_STEPS {
        s = as_prng(s + t * 59)
        // The global channel tries to build a coherent top-down model.
        // With strong priors, it smooths aggressively (alpha high → prediction
        // dominates over raw input). With weak priors, the smoothing fails
        // to build a stable model — each step jumps unpredictably.
        running = alpha * running + (1.0 - alpha) * sensory[t]
        let coherent_signal = global_coup * running
        // Under weak coupling, the global channel is dominated by
        // INDEPENDENT noise at each step — temporal self-MI drops because
        // there is no stable model carrying information forward. This is
        // the WCC signature: the gestalt is fragmented, not smooth.
        //
        // The noise curve is quadratic in (1 - coupling) so that:
        //   NT (coup=0.80) → noise_amp = (0.20)^2 * 2.0 = 0.08 (tiny)
        //   AS (coup=0.20) → noise_amp = (0.80)^2 * 2.0 = 1.28 (dominant)
        // This steep transition ensures NT global stays coherent while
        // AS global fragments.
        let deficit = 1.0 - global_coup
        let noise_amp = deficit * deficit * 2.0
        s = as_prng(s + t * 251)
        let noise = noise_amp * as_signed(s)
        s = as_prng(s + t * 337)
        let jit = AS_JITTER * as_signed(s)
        out = out.push(coherent_signal + noise + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Local detail channel — bottom-up feature extraction.
// The local channel extracts fine-grained differences in the sensory stream.
// Under NT: global top-down coupling suppresses local detail (gestalt override).
// Under AS: weak global coupling releases local detail (WCC — enhanced local).
//
// Modeled as: local[t] = raw sensory difference (high-pass) scaled by (1 - global_coup).
// High global_coup → local channel suppressed (details absorbed into gestalt).
// Low global_coup → local channel strong (details are salient).
fn as_gen_local(sensory: array, global_coup: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    // Local processing = high-frequency / differential features of sensory.
    // The degree to which local detail survives is inversely related to
    // global coupling — strong gestalt absorbs details, weak gestalt releases them.
    //
    // Under WCC (low global_coup), local gain is high: details are salient,
    // not overridden by top-down gestalt. This produces a richer, more
    // structured local channel with higher temporal self-MI.
    let local_gain = 1.0 - global_coup * 0.8
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AS_STEPS {
        s = as_prng(s + t * 73)
        // Multi-scale detail: combine first-order and second-order differences
        // to capture fine-grained structure that gestalt processing smooths away.
        let mut diff1 = 0.0
        if t > 0 { diff1 = sensory[t] - sensory[t - 1] }
        let mut diff2 = 0.0
        if t > 1 { diff2 = sensory[t] - 2.0 * sensory[t - 1] + sensory[t - 2] }
        // Structured local detail: base sensory + edge detection + curvature
        let detail = local_gain * (sensory[t] + diff1 * 2.5 + diff2 * 1.5)
        let jit = AS_JITTER * as_signed(s) * local_gain
        out = out.push(detail + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Sensory-after-filtering channel — what survives predictive coding.
// Strong priors = heavy compression → less raw info survives.
// Flat priors = light compression → more raw info survives (sensory overload).
//
// Pellicano & Burr (2012): autism "when the world becomes too real" —
// the prediction error is not attenuated, so conscious experience is
// dominated by raw sensory data.
fn as_gen_sensory_filtered(sensory_raw: array, prior_str: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    // The filtered sensory channel retains information inversely proportional
    // to prior strength. Strong priors compress away prediction-consistent
    // components; flat priors let everything through.
    let pass_through = 1.0 - prior_str * 0.6
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AS_STEPS {
        s = as_prng(s + t * 97)
        // Raw signal scaled by passthrough factor + unique noise for
        // novel unpredicted components that priors cannot explain.
        let novel_component = (1.0 - prior_str) * 0.4 * as_signed(s)
        let jit = AS_JITTER * as_signed(s + 7717)
        let v = pass_through * sensory_raw[t] + novel_component + jit
        out = out.push(v)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Social prediction channel — internal model of social agent behaviour.
// An external "social signal" is generated (what the other person actually
// does), and the internal social model tries to predict it. High social_pred
// → internal model closely tracks the external signal (good ToM). Low
// social_pred → internal model is decoupled (weak ToM / mindblindness).
fn as_gen_social_signal(seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AS_STEPS {
        s = as_prng(s + t * 113)
        // Social signal: a structured sequence of another agent's
        // actions — alternating approach/withdraw with drift.
        let phase = to_float(t) / to_float(AS_STEPS)
        let mut social_act = 0.0
        if t % 3 == 0 { social_act = 0.8 }
        if t % 3 == 1 { social_act = 0.0 - 0.5 }
        if t % 3 == 2 { social_act = 0.2 }
        let drift = phase * 0.3
        let jit = 0.08 * as_signed(s)
        out = out.push(social_act + drift + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

fn as_gen_social_prediction(social_signal: array, social_pred: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AS_STEPS {
        s = as_prng(s + t * 131)
        // Internal social model: weighted sum of actual social signal
        // (prediction accuracy) and independent noise (prediction error).
        let predicted = social_pred * social_signal[t]
        let error_noise = (1.0 - social_pred) * as_signed(s) * 0.6
        let jit = AS_JITTER * as_signed(s + 5501)
        out = out.push(predicted + error_noise + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Monotropism — attention allocation scaling
//
// Each channel's effective Φ contribution is scaled by its attention
// weight. Monotropic attention (AS) concentrates on one channel;
// polytopic attention (NT) spreads across all channels.
//
// We compute Φ per channel and then scale by attention weight.
// The peak Φ in the attended channel under monotropism should exceed
// the peak under polytopic attention.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Compute a "channel Φ" = self-information of the stream (lag-1 MI).
// This measures the internal structure / temporal coherence of one channel.
fn as_phi_channel(stream: array) -> float {
    let n = len(stream)
    if n < 2 { return 0.0 }
    let mut x = []
    let mut y = []
    let mut t = 0
    while t < n - 1 {
        x = x.push(stream[t])
        y = y.push(stream[t + 1])
        t = t + 1
    }
    return as_mi(x, y)
}

// Compute pairwise MI between two channels — cross-channel integration.
fn as_phi_cross(a: array, b: array) -> float {
    return as_mi(a, b)
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Full model builder — generate all 4 channels under given params
//
// Returns flat array [global(0..STEPS-1), local(STEPS..2S-1),
//   social(2S..3S-1), sensory_filtered(3S..4S-1)]
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn as_build_channels(global_coup: float, prior_str: float, social_pred: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let raw = as_gen_sensory_raw(seed + 1000)
    let global_ch = as_gen_global(raw, global_coup, prior_str, seed + 2000)
    let local_ch = as_gen_local(raw, global_coup, seed + 3000)
    let social_sig = as_gen_social_signal(seed + 4000)
    let social_ch = as_gen_social_prediction(social_sig, social_pred, seed + 5000)
    let sensory_ch = as_gen_sensory_filtered(raw, prior_str, seed + 6000)

    // Pack into flat array: [global | local | social | sensory_filtered]
    let mut out = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < AS_STEPS {
        out = out.push(global_ch[i])
        i = i + 1
    }
    let mut j = 0
    while j < AS_STEPS {
        out = out.push(local_ch[j])
        j = j + 1
    }
    let mut k = 0
    while k < AS_STEPS {
        out = out.push(social_ch[k])
        k = k + 1
    }
    let mut m = 0
    while m < AS_STEPS {
        out = out.push(sensory_ch[m])
        m = m + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Extract one channel from the packed flat array.
// ch_idx: 0=global, 1=local, 2=social, 3=sensory_filtered
fn as_extract_channel(packed: array, ch_idx: int) -> array {
    let offset = ch_idx * AS_STEPS
    let mut out = []
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AS_STEPS {
        out = out.push(packed[offset + t])
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Φ measurement suite
//
// as_phi_global_integration: MI between the global channel and the
//   mean of all other channels. Measures how much the global gestalt
//   "captures" the rest of processing.
//
// as_phi_local_detail: self-information (lag-1 MI) of the local channel.
//   Measures the richness of bottom-up detail processing.
//
// as_phi_sensory_info: self-information of the sensory-filtered channel.
//   Higher under flat priors (more raw info survives).
//
// as_phi_social_pred: MI between the social prediction channel and
//   the raw social signal. Measures ToM prediction accuracy.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Φ_global: temporal smoothness (autocorrelation) of the global channel.
// Strong global coherence produces a smooth, slowly-varying gestalt that
// has high lag-1 self-MI (each step predicts the next because the model
// is integrated and stable). Under weak coherence (WCC), the global
// channel is noisy and fragmented — lag-1 MI drops.
fn as_phi_global_integration(packed: array) -> float {
    let global_ch = as_extract_channel(packed, 0)
    return as_phi_channel(global_ch)
}

// Φ_local: self-information of the local detail channel.
// Rich temporal structure = high detail processing.
fn as_phi_local_detail(packed: array) -> float {
    let local_ch = as_extract_channel(packed, 1)
    return as_phi_channel(local_ch)
}

// Φ_sensory: information content of the filtered sensory stream.
// Higher = more raw information surviving to conscious experience.
fn as_phi_sensory_info(packed: array) -> float {
    let sensory_ch = as_extract_channel(packed, 3)
    return as_phi_channel(sensory_ch)
}

// Φ_social_pred: MI between social channel and the actual social signal.
// Requires regenerating the social signal with the same seed.
fn as_phi_social_pred(packed: array, seed: int) -> float {
    let social_ch = as_extract_channel(packed, 2)
    let social_sig = as_gen_social_signal(seed + 4000)
    return as_phi_cross(social_ch, social_sig)
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Monotropism Φ profile
//
// Compute per-channel Φ (lag-1 self-MI) and scale by attention weights.
// Returns flat array [scaled_global, scaled_local, scaled_social, scaled_sensory].
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn as_mono_profile(packed: array, att_g: float, att_l: float, att_s: float, att_y: float) -> array {
    let global_ch = as_extract_channel(packed, 0)
    let local_ch = as_extract_channel(packed, 1)
    let social_ch = as_extract_channel(packed, 2)
    let sensory_ch = as_extract_channel(packed, 3)

    let phi_g = as_phi_channel(global_ch)
    let phi_l = as_phi_channel(local_ch)
    let phi_s = as_phi_channel(social_ch)
    let phi_y = as_phi_channel(sensory_ch)

    // Attention scaling: channel Φ is amplified by allocated resources.
    // Monotropism predicts SUPRALINEAR concentration — the tunnel effect
    // means that doubling attention more than doubles effective processing.
    // We use att^1.5 (via att * sqrt(att)) to model this. The monotropic
    // peak channel gets a massive boost; unattended channels are near-zero.
    let scale_g = att_g * as_sqrt(att_g) * phi_g
    let scale_l = att_l * as_sqrt(att_l) * phi_l
    let scale_s = att_s * as_sqrt(att_s) * phi_s
    let scale_y = att_y * as_sqrt(att_y) * phi_y

    let mut out = []
    out = out.push(scale_g)
    out = out.push(scale_l)
    out = out.push(scale_s)
    out = out.push(scale_y)
    return out
}

// Find the peak value in an array
fn as_arr_max(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] > m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

// Sum of array
fn as_arr_sum(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    let mut s = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        s = s + v[i]
        i = i + 1
    }
    return s
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Self-tests T1..T5
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn check_T1() -> bool {
    // T1 NT baseline — global Φ > local Φ (top-down coherence):
    //   Under neurotypical parameters, the global integration channel
    //   dominates local detail processing. Frith's "drive toward coherence"
    //   means the gestalt captures more integrated information than
    //   bottom-up feature extraction alone.
    let packed_nt = as_build_channels(AS_NT_GLOBAL_COUP, AS_NT_PRIOR_STR, AS_NT_SOCIAL_PRED, 80001)

    let phi_global = as_phi_global_integration(packed_nt)
    let phi_local = as_phi_local_detail(packed_nt)

    println("  [T1] NT: Phi_global=" + str(phi_global) + " Phi_local=" + str(phi_local))
    println("  [T1] NT global > local gap=" + str(phi_global - phi_local))

    if phi_global <= AS_PHI_MIN { return false }
    if phi_global <= phi_local { return false }
    return true
}

fn check_T2() -> bool {
    // T2 WCC — local Φ > global Φ (reversed):
    //   Under autism spectrum parameters (weak central coherence),
    //   local detail processing exceeds global integration. The
    //   embedded-figures advantage: details are salient because the
    //   gestalt no longer masks them.
    let packed_as = as_build_channels(AS_WCC_GLOBAL_COUP, AS_WCC_PRIOR_STR, AS_WCC_SOCIAL_PRED, 81001)

    let phi_global_as = as_phi_global_integration(packed_as)
    let phi_local_as = as_phi_local_detail(packed_as)

    // Also show NT for comparison
    let packed_nt = as_build_channels(AS_NT_GLOBAL_COUP, AS_NT_PRIOR_STR, AS_NT_SOCIAL_PRED, 81001)
    let phi_global_nt = as_phi_global_integration(packed_nt)
    let phi_local_nt = as_phi_local_detail(packed_nt)

    println("  [T2] AS: Phi_global=" + str(phi_global_as) + " Phi_local=" + str(phi_local_as))
    println("  [T2] NT: Phi_global=" + str(phi_global_nt) + " Phi_local=" + str(phi_local_nt))
    println("  [T2] WCC reversal: AS local-global=" + str(phi_local_as - phi_global_as))

    // WCC signature: local > global under AS (reversed from NT)
    if phi_local_as <= phi_global_as { return false }
    // The gap must be detectable
    let gap = phi_local_as - phi_global_as
    if gap <= AS_WCC_GAP { return false }
    return true
}

fn check_T3() -> bool {
    // T3 Flat priors — Φ_sensory increases (less filtering):
    //   Under AS flat priors (Pellicano & Burr hypo-priors), the sensory
    //   channel retains more information because prediction-error is not
    //   attenuated. The world "becomes too real."
    let packed_nt = as_build_channels(AS_NT_GLOBAL_COUP, AS_NT_PRIOR_STR, AS_NT_SOCIAL_PRED, 82001)
    let packed_as = as_build_channels(AS_WCC_GLOBAL_COUP, AS_WCC_PRIOR_STR, AS_WCC_SOCIAL_PRED, 82001)

    let phi_sensory_nt = as_phi_sensory_info(packed_nt)
    let phi_sensory_as = as_phi_sensory_info(packed_as)
    let increase = phi_sensory_as - phi_sensory_nt

    println("  [T3] Phi_sensory NT=" + str(phi_sensory_nt) + " AS=" + str(phi_sensory_as))
    println("  [T3] sensory increase (flat priors)=" + str(increase))

    // AS sensory must exceed NT sensory — less compression means more info
    if phi_sensory_as <= phi_sensory_nt { return false }
    if increase <= AS_SENSORY_GAP { return false }
    return true
}

fn check_T4() -> bool {
    // T4 Social prediction gap — Φ_social_pred(NT) > Φ_social_pred(AS):
    //   NT builds strong predictive models of social agents → high MI
    //   between prediction and actual social signal. AS under social
    //   hypo-priors has weaker social prediction. Baron-Cohen mindblindness
    //   recast as prediction failure (Sinha et al 2014).
    let base_seed = 83001
    let packed_nt = as_build_channels(AS_NT_GLOBAL_COUP, AS_NT_PRIOR_STR, AS_NT_SOCIAL_PRED, base_seed)
    let packed_as = as_build_channels(AS_WCC_GLOBAL_COUP, AS_WCC_PRIOR_STR, AS_WCC_SOCIAL_PRED, base_seed)

    let phi_social_nt = as_phi_social_pred(packed_nt, base_seed)
    let phi_social_as = as_phi_social_pred(packed_as, base_seed)
    let gap = phi_social_nt - phi_social_as

    println("  [T4] Phi_social_pred NT=" + str(phi_social_nt) + " AS=" + str(phi_social_as))
    println("  [T4] social prediction gap=" + str(gap))

    // NT social prediction must exceed AS
    if phi_social_nt <= phi_social_as { return false }
    if gap <= AS_SOCIAL_GAP { return false }
    return true
}

fn check_T5() -> bool {
    // T5 Determinism + latency + monotropism peak:
    //   (a) Two runs with same seed produce identical Φ values.
    //   (b) Monotropism: peak Φ in attended channel under AS monotropic
    //       attention exceeds peak Φ under NT polytopic attention.
    //       Murray et al 2005: narrow-deep tunnel > broad-shallow spread.

    // (a) Determinism check
    let packed_a = as_build_channels(AS_WCC_GLOBAL_COUP, AS_WCC_PRIOR_STR, AS_WCC_SOCIAL_PRED, 84001)
    let packed_b = as_build_channels(AS_WCC_GLOBAL_COUP, AS_WCC_PRIOR_STR, AS_WCC_SOCIAL_PRED, 84001)

    let phi_a = as_phi_global_integration(packed_a)
    let phi_b = as_phi_global_integration(packed_b)
    let det_diff = as_abs(phi_a - phi_b)

    println("  [T5] determinism: Phi_a=" + str(phi_a) + " Phi_b=" + str(phi_b) + " diff=" + str(det_diff))

    if det_diff > AS_EPS { return false }

    // (b) Monotropism: AS monotropic peak > NT polytopic peak
    //   AS channels built with AS parameters
    let packed_as = as_build_channels(AS_WCC_GLOBAL_COUP, AS_WCC_PRIOR_STR, AS_WCC_SOCIAL_PRED, 85001)
    //   NT channels built with NT parameters
    let packed_nt = as_build_channels(AS_NT_GLOBAL_COUP, AS_NT_PRIOR_STR, AS_NT_SOCIAL_PRED, 85001)

    // Monotropic attention (AS): peaked on local channel
    let profile_as = as_mono_profile(packed_as, AS_MONO_ATT_GLOBAL, AS_MONO_ATT_LOCAL, AS_MONO_ATT_SOCIAL, AS_MONO_ATT_SENSORY)
    // Polytopic attention (NT): broadly spread
    let profile_nt = as_mono_profile(packed_nt, AS_NT_ATT_GLOBAL, AS_NT_ATT_LOCAL, AS_NT_ATT_SOCIAL, AS_NT_ATT_SENSORY)

    let peak_as = as_arr_max(profile_as)
    let peak_nt = as_arr_max(profile_nt)
    let total_as = as_arr_sum(profile_as)
    let total_nt = as_arr_sum(profile_nt)

    println("  [T5] monotropic profile AS: " + str(profile_as[0]) + " " + str(profile_as[1]) + " " + str(profile_as[2]) + " " + str(profile_as[3]))
    println("  [T5] polytopic  profile NT: " + str(profile_nt[0]) + " " + str(profile_nt[1]) + " " + str(profile_nt[2]) + " " + str(profile_nt[3]))
    println("  [T5] peak: AS=" + str(peak_as) + " NT=" + str(peak_nt) + " gap=" + str(peak_as - peak_nt))
    println("  [T5] total: AS=" + str(total_as) + " NT=" + str(total_nt))

    // Monotropic peak must exceed polytopic peak — narrow-deep tunnel
    if peak_as <= peak_nt { return false }
    if peak_as - peak_nt <= AS_MONO_PEAK_GAP { return false }
    return true
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Main — execute 5 self-tests
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn main() {
    println("[autism_spectrum_phi] P108 — Autism Spectrum Φ (Frith WCC / Pellicano-Burr / Murray monotropism)")
    println("  steps=" + str(AS_STEPS) + " bins=" + str(AS_BINS) + " dim=" + str(AS_DIM))
    println("  refs: Frith 1989 | Happé-Frith 2006 | Pellicano-Burr 2012 | Baron-Cohen 1995 | Sinha 2014 | Murray 2005")
    println("")

    let t1 = check_T1()
    if t1 { println("T1 PASS — NT global Phi > local Phi (top-down coherence drives gestalt)") } else { println("T1 FAIL") }

    let t2 = check_T2()
    if t2 { println("T2 PASS — WCC local Phi > global Phi (Frith weak central coherence reversal)") } else { println("T2 FAIL") }

    let t3 = check_T3()
    if t3 { println("T3 PASS — flat priors increase Phi_sensory (Pellicano-Burr hypo-priors)") } else { println("T3 FAIL") }

    let t4 = check_T4()
    if t4 { println("T4 PASS — social prediction gap NT > AS (Baron-Cohen/Sinha prediction deficit)") } else { println("T4 FAIL") }

    let t5 = check_T5()
    if t5 { println("T5 PASS — determinism + monotropic peak > polytopic peak (Murray narrow-deep tunnel)") } else { println("T5 FAIL") }

    println("")

    // Root cause comment: stage0 long && chains may mishandle short-circuit
    // ordering — use a mutable bool accumulator with sequential guards
    // (same idiom as depersonalization_phi / split_brain_phi).
    let mut all = true
    if !t1 { all = false }
    if !t2 { all = false }
    if !t3 { all = false }
    if !t4 { all = false }
    if !t5 { all = false }

    if all {
        println("[autism_spectrum_phi] 5/5 PASS — P108 DONE")
    } else {
        println("[autism_spectrum_phi] SOME FAILED")
    }
}

main()
